body:
### Example code

Verilog file `top.v`:

```Verilog
module top (o, clk, wire3, wire7);
  output [12:0] o;
  input clk;
  input signed [2:0] wire3;
  input [6:0] wire7;

  reg signed [5:0] reg6 = 0;
  reg signed [6:0] reg7 = 0;
  assign o = {reg6, reg7};

  always @(posedge clk) begin
     reg7 <= wire7;
     reg6 <= wire3 >> reg7;
   end
endmodule
```

C++ file `main.cpp`:

```cpp
#include "verilated.h"
#include "Vtop.h"

#include <bitset>
#include <iostream>

//======================

int main(int argc, char** argv, char**) {
    // Setup context, defaults, and parse command line
    Verilated::debug(0);
    const std::unique_ptr<VerilatedContext> contextp{new VerilatedContext};
    contextp->commandArgs(argc, argv);

    // Construct the Verilated model, from Vtop.h generated from Verilating
    const std::unique_ptr<Vtop> topp{new Vtop{contextp.get()}};

    // Simulate
    topp->clk = 0;
    topp->eval();
    topp->wire7 = 2;
    topp->clk = 1;
    topp->eval();
    std::cout << "o = " << std::bitset<16>(topp->o) << std::endl;
    // NOTE: now reg7 is expected to be 2

    topp->clk = 0;
    topp->eval();
    topp->wire3 = 4;
    topp->wire7 = 0;
    topp->clk = 1;
    topp->eval();

    std::cout << "---" << std::endl;
    std::cout << "o = " << std::bitset<16>(topp->o) << std::endl;

    // Final model cleanup
    topp->final();
    return 0;
}
```

Verilator cmdline:

```
$ ./bin/verilator -cc -exe -build -Wno-WIDTHEXPAND top.v main.cpp
```

Outputs of `Vtop`:

```
$ ./obj_dir/Vtop
o = 0000000000000010
---
o = 0000011110000000
```

Verilator outputs `reg6 = 6'b001111` after we set `wire3 = 3'b100` and `reg7 = 7'b0000010`, which seems to be wrong.

Actually, I'm still not very sure whether `wire3` and `reg7` should be extended to 7-bit or truncated to 3-bit after reading the Verilog standard (IEEE Std 1364™-2005). Seems that Verilator extended `wire3` to 6-bit. I also tried Yosys and it extended both of them to 7-bit, then truncated to 6-bit to fit `reg6`. So I fired this issue here.

Sorry if this is not a real bug to you.

### Verilator version

The latest git master (`ee5c0a29024dc6777491e78c913e9efc1bcdbe6f`).

### OS version

**WSL2** on Windows (`5.15.90.1-microsoft-standard-WSL2`)
The distribution I used was Debian 10.
